You were wrong about the King, it seems. 

Just when you were sure the King's urgency for your arrival is but an exaggeration, you had been called in haste to perform divination. You stand in front of the royal palace, your back against his tall form as your hands hovering under a prepared scapula, holding a torched hardwood brand that's slowly biting a dip in its underside. 

"Tell me," the King had said, his body draped over the carved throne, the infamous Daji to his side, her palm massaging into his shoulders. "Will the Shang thrive on in glory?" And as lazy his tone was as his form, the steel in his eyes chilled you.

You felt his stare even now, unseeing his face. But no matter. To you, the oracle bone's ritual process has been written into your mind, from [[years of practice back in the Qiang state|CH1: Context: Qiang 2]]. Your hand moved, almost mindlessly, aligning the scorched hollows from bottom to top as your eyes searched for patterns, cracks, signs. 

The preparations are soon finished in making. [[You leaned forward to take a look at the cracks.|CH1: Reading the bone]]


