:: CH2: Daji and King conversation {"position":"1800,950","size":"100,100"}
"Yes, my favored." Said the King, and it dawned on you just then that you were not the only one hiding.

"At long last!" Daji's voice floated from within the room. "I thought he meant to stay the night." 

"I bare no mind to entertain that spoilt child." Said the King with a scoff. "In his prescence, I cannot speak freely of my...plans, that is."

A rustle, and Daji's voice is now a murmur. "And what did you have in mind, my King?"

The King laughed brusquely. "Nights with you are a given, dear." He said. "And you know what I meant. The boy would spread my plan of secret invasion like wildfire before my men are ready to march."

You had to stifle a gasp before it alerted the King and his consort. //An invasion into Gui, still? Despite the bone's message?//

Lost in thought, you almost failed to notice Daji stepping from the doors, a furtive look upon her face. She glanced around, but did not see you. As she swiftly walked away, you could not help but notice that she was walking in the direction of Lutai in the city. 

[[What is she up to?|CH2: Daji speaks with prisoner]]


:: CH2: Daji speaks with prisoner {"position":"1700,1100","size":"100,100"}
Daji took no notice of you trailing behind her. As workers and guards surrounding Lutai turned their backs, she slipped through a back door you would not have seen otherwise. You followed suit, curiosity brewing.

Instead of entering Lutai itself, Daji approached an ordinary straw shed nearby. You plastered your ear to a small crack upon the wall, and listened.

"--I've no care for you as much as that snake, Dixin." A voice you did not recognize snarled, followed by a rattle of bronze scraping against each other. Your eyes widened. A man, bound in chains.

An airy chuckle stopped him short. "You made that quite clear when you had a knife pointing to my heart, peasant." Said Daji, her tone mocking. "Whom were you truly aiming it for? Me, or the King?" 

"Does it matter?" More sounds of metal, clinking together as the man was likely struggling against his chains amidst shout. "You and that beast of a man are the poisons of this world! Needless war, higher taxation--people starve as you party amongst pools of liquor. Any blood on my knife would've been a blessing from spirits."

"You can curse and spit all you want," Daji's voice was soft, sending pinpricks down your back. "But your 'needless wars' are the only thing holding up this kingdom's failing states together. Why resist then, when the Shang thrives as one under my King?"

The chains thrashed even harder as the man cried out in rage. "You dare! You shameless consort--"

"You know of the punishments we have for assassinations like yours," said Daji. "If I were you, I wouldn't waste my breath while I still had it."

With a swing and a click of the door, all was silent. 

"Come inside." The voice said suddenly. You jumped at the words, and gave a sweeping look around the shed. You were the only one there, now, apart from the man calling for you. 

The voice sighed, "I know you're there, fool."

[[With a shaky breath, you opened the door and slipped in.|CH2: Player talk to prisoner]]


:: CH2: Inform player of Zhou rebel {"position":"1700,1350","size":"100,100"}
The man paused, and lifted his head to fully look at you. You felt his eyes take in your form, your stance, your face. He must've saw something there, as he began to spoke.

"Who I am is unimportant." He said. "It is where I'm from that matters." His eyes searched yours once more, and his speech lowered to a faint whisper. "I am from the Zhou state."

The Zhou. You know of them, of couse, as one of the many states under Shang's ruling.

"You must know by now that the King has long lost himself to decadence and corruption," the man said. "There may be no way out for me, but perhaps you can carry on my mission."

"You want me to kill the King?!" You whisper-shouted. 

